Java Encapsulation Assignment Answers
1. What is Encapsulation? Why is it called Data Hiding?
Encapsulation is the process of wrapping data (variables) and the code acting on that data (methods) together as a single unit. 
In Java, this is achieved by creating a class.
It is called Data Hiding because it restricts direct access to the data members of a class. By making variables private,
you hide the internal state of the object from the outside world, ensuring that data can only be accessed or modified through authorized methods.
2. Important Features of Encapsulation
Data Protection: Prevents unauthorized external code from modifying internal data.
Modularity: The source code for a class can be written and maintained independently.
Flexibility: You can make variables "read-only" or "write-only" by omitting specific getter or setter methods.
3. Getter and Setter Methods
These are public methods used to access and update the value of a private variable.
Getter: Returns the variable value.
Setter: Updates the variable value.
Example:
java
public class Student {
    private String name; // private variable

    public String getName() { return name; } // Getter
    public void setName(String newName) { this.name = newName; } // Setter
}
Use code with caution.
4. Use of this Keyword
The this keyword refers to the current instance of the class. It is primarily used to resolve ambiguity
when instance variables and parameters have the same name.
Example:
java
public class Car {
    String model;
    Car(String model) {
        this.model = model; // "this.model" is the class variable, "model" is the parameter
    }
}
Use code with caution.
5. Advantages of Encapsulation
Better Control: You can add logic (like validation) inside setter methods before changing data.
Security: Protects the integrity of the data.
Easy Testing: Encapsulated code is easier to unit test.
Maintenance: You can change the internal implementation without affecting the classes that use it.
6. How to Achieve Encapsulation
To achieve encapsulation in Java:
Declare the class variables as private.
Provide public get and set methods to access/modify those variables.
Complete Example:
java
class Account {
    private double balance; // Data hidden

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    public void setBalance(double amount) {
        if(amount > 0) { // Validation logic
            this.balance = amount;
        }
    }
}
